gmd:title.gco:CharacterString: Alternative Fuel Retail Fueling Sites: Indiana, 2006

gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: Alternative fuel retail fueling sites in the state of Indiana. Alternative fuels are described as biodiesel (B2, B5, B10, and B20) as well as ethanol (E85).

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: The availability of alternative fuels is becoming more widespread because of increasing demand that is driven by consumption, marketing and politics. Alternative fuels are renewable or good for the environment because they are renewable and potentially have lower emissions. They are politically described as increasing local jobs and the economy and lowering demand on foreign oil. Consumption of these fuels increases as more vehicles capable of burning mixtures increases. This data set locates alternative fuel retail fuel sites.

gmd:supplementalInformation.gco:CharacterString: Retail fueling sites listed on the National Ethanol Vehicle Coalition (NEVC) and National Biodiesel Board (NBB) Web sites for Indiana were located by address information and adjusted using orthophotography.

gmd:measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: All sites listed on the NEVC and NBB Web sites on August 16, 2006, for Indiana are represented in this dataset.

The location information was printed from the NEVC and NBB Web sites on August 16, 2006. This information was typed into a Microsoft Excel spreadsheet and manually checked for accuracy. The fuel type was entered as yes or no and crosschecked with the original printouts.

GoogleEarth http://earth.google.com/ was used to locate the retail fueling site by address. The latitude and longitude were documented on a Microsoft Excel spreadsheet. The data was converted to decimal degree locations in Microsoft Excel. The spreadsheet was imported into ESRI ArcMap and the decimal degree locations were automatically plotted. The 2005 Indiana orthophotgraphy (1 foot or 6 inch where available) were loaded and the facility points were adjusted to make sure they were located on the facility property.

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: A Web search for alternative retail fuel sites in Indiana led to the National Ethanol Vehicle Coalition and National Biodiesel Board Internet sites. The location information was printed from the NEVC and NBB Web sites on August 16, 2006. This information was typed into a Microsoft Excel spreadsheet and manually checked for accuracy. The fuel type was entered as yes, for available, or no, for not available, and crosschecked with the original printouts. GoogleEarth http://earth.google.com/ was used to locate the retail fueling site by address. The latitude and longitude were documented on the Microsoft Excel spreadsheet by manual documentation. Using the calculate function in Excel the decimal degree locations were computed. The spreadsheet was imported into ESRI ArcMap and the decimal degree locations were automatically plotted. The 2005 Indiana orthophotgraphy (1 foot or 6 inch where available) were loaded into the ArcMap project and the facility point moved to make sure it was located on the facility property, in many cases the point was placed on the driveway into the facility. The Universal Transfer Mercator zone 16 coordinates were added to the data table using ESRI ArcMap.

This metadata was pre-parsed and parsed using CNS (Chew and Spit v 2.6.1) and MP (Metadata Parser v 2.7.1) software written by Peter N. Schweitzer (U.S. Geological Survey). The errors generated by MP were all addressed and corrected.
Orthophotography used to locate point on facility property.
